metadata.name: Cometary coma #59
metadata.description:
Made of ice and comet dust.
Nebulous envelope surrounding the nucleus of a comet.
Formed when passing close to the Sun on its highly elliptical orbit.

As the comet warms, parts of it sublimate.

metadata.description: "You take the blue pill... the story ends, you wake up in your bed and believe whatever you want to believe. You take the red pill... you stay in Wonderland, and I show you how deep the rabbit hole goes"

metadata.name: Sands of Time #19
metadata.description:
+ 50% of proceeds will be donated to Cure Parkinson's
+ Minters get 4.5% of royalties from secondary sales
+ Press 1 to 8 to change the resolution of the render (1: lowest resolution, 8: highest resolution)

----

STATEMENT

The sands of time rise up,
Their scapes so bold and old,
In their dance with the winds,
As light and shadow dance and play,
In this land of endless day.
A sight of quiet grace,
On a canvas of the desert's face.
A song of resilience,
In a world that changes by the hour.

"Sands of Time" is a rhetoric of transience and impermanence inspired by the dunes. It is a comtemplation of the passing of time, the inevitability of change, and the beauty that can be found in impermanence. It is an invitation to reflect on the fluidity of life and our own place within the grander scheme of things. A testament to the resilience and grit required to survive in a constantly changing world. Despite the harsh conditions and ever-present threat of change, the desert sands endure, shifting but not breaking; their beauty and strength undiminished.

Made of several overlapping curved lines, each piece is a depiction of movement and fluidity, symbolizing sands in a constant state of motion. The curves blend and mix, creating new patterns and hues where they overlap, much like the way that life experiences blend and mix to create new and unique outcomes. The uneven distribution of grains across each piece represents timelessness. Areas of low accumulation of grains are a reminder of the years of constant erosion. The sands of time have existed and will exist in a state of constant motion and change for eons, for the lifetime. This way, each piece also evokes nostalgia, as we ponder on our past lives.

“It’s your reaction to adversity, not adversity itself that determines how your life’s story will develop.” ― Dieter F. Uchtdorf

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #84
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #58
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: Landstreicherin #96
metadata.description:
This is an update of my Landstreicher project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/9606). All proceeds of primary and secondary go to NGO "Save the Children".

For higher resolution renderings, e.g. 4x resolution of current canvas size: Open the artwork in its own browser tab, add the parameter *&highres=4* to the url and reload. e.g. https://gateway.fxhash2.xyz/ipfs/<something>/?fxhash=ooXrQmk42nyJd4HAB63v7jJ9R27DiwcbwDaUEYuX3FvGDzfwNog&highres=4 . Adapt this procedure for 8x resolution or similar.

For exporting press *e*.

The source code is here: https://github.com/sektionschef/Landstreicherin 
Stefan Schwaha, @sektionschef, https://digitalitility.com/

metadata.name: simpel #22
metadata.description:
"simpel" german for basic/simple is my first collection that features generative art. The projects focus is layed on basic shapes and colors without using shaders or animations. 
In this world where everyone tries to be better and different, looking back at the "simpel" things might be a good choice.

“Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication.” — Leonardo da Vinci
“Less is more.” — Mies van der Rohe

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @nicolus_999 - nicolus_genArt

metadata.name: Clutter #58
metadata.description:
People have lots of useless stuff, some more than others, some less. Not only do they spend money buying things they don't need, but some of them require obligatory extra costs and care for proper upkeep. Let's say you buy a fancy car. You constantly make sure it doesn't get scratched, you wash it regularly, you say "careful about the seats" and you never allow someone to eat in it, since vacuuming is hardly something you like doing. Overall, it's just a burden.

Having something forces you to change your behavior. That's not necessarily bad, but it is a fact.
Everything you own, ends up owning you.

metadata.name: TRQ.1 #12
metadata.description:
The aesthetics of the work is inspired by the work of the Brazilian artist DIONISIO DEL SANTO, above all, the formal simplification, the use of geometric figures, in addition to planes and colors, in a simplified way, the work also makes reference to the principles of Concretism, as a movement artistic.

Features:
PALETTES
In total, the work has fifteen different color palettes, with percentages of probability of occurrence varying between 2% and 15%.

FORMES
The images are structured using only three simple shapes (square, rectangle and triangle) proportional to each other. Said shapes can also be rotated and interleaved with empty squares.
The use of each one of the forms follows three different combination patterns, according to the description and percentages of occurrence indicated below:
“+++” – 50% | full square + triangle
“++” – 35% | rectangle + triangle
“+” – 15% | just triangle

INVERSÉ
One of the rare features, with only a 10% probability, is the occurrence of the inverted color palette, in which the colors of the background, simple shapes and frame, are put in negative.

VECTEUR
The background was structured following two possible direction vectors (horizontal – 40% or vertical – 60%).

MODULES
The canvas can be subdivided following three different modulations, which can be 3X3 (20% chance), 4X4 (45% chance) or 5X5 (35% chance).

September 01, 2022.
Generative token by Paivei made with p5js for FxHash.
